{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525817","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525817"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:17:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:17:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14093"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14093","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14093"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.44,0.24,0.1,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6761"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109562"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6761","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6761"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14093"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91937"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"2746"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"8189"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14744"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14745"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34821"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34905"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40997"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109562","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109562"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 69-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of a rash on the front of both lower legs. He reports that the affected areas are slightly itchy but not painful. He enjoys hiking in the National park on his weekends and is a keen cyclist mid-week. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus diagnosed 10 years ago, and his most recent Hb1Ac was 8.2%. His regular medications include metformin and gliclazide. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Inspection of his lower legs reveals bilateral, raised, waxy plaques on the anterior tibial surfaces (Image). The surrounding skin appears normal, and there is no pitting oedema. There are no similar rashes elsewhere on his body.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increase gliclazide dose","Measure thyroid function tests","Prescribe topical corticosteroids","Commence compression stockings","Commence oral antibiotics"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation described is highly suggestive of pretibial myxoedema, a dermatological manifestation typically associated with Graves\u0027 disease. Given this finding, the most appropriate next step is to \u003Cstrong\u003Emeasure thyroid function tests\u003C/strong\u003E. This will help confirm or rule out underlying thyroid dysfunction, which is crucial for proper management. Patients with pretibial myxoedema will not necessarily have overt signs of Graves\u0027 disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrescribing topical corticosteroids\u003C/strong\u003E might provide some symptomatic relief for the skin lesions, but it does not address the underlying cause. Topical steroids are affective against eczema which has a more dry appearance and less likely to be only on the anterior lower legs. While topical corticosteroids can be part of the treatment plan for pretibial myxoedema, they should not be the first step before confirming the diagnosis and underlying thyroid status.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing the gliclazide dose\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate in this context. While the patient has diabetes, the skin changes described are not typical of diabetic dermopathy or other diabetes-related skin conditions. Moreover, hypothyroidism affects the liver secretion of glycogen and absorption of glucose so increasing diabetes medication without further investigation could potentially lead to hypoglycemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing compression stockings\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most appropriate first step. This would not be determining the cause of the problem, nor treating it. Compression stockings have a role in lymphoedema and in non-healing ulcers which is not demonstrated in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing oral antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in this case. The description of the skin lesions does not suggest a bacterial infection - erythematous and tenderness would be more prevalent. Pretibial myxoedema is an autoimmune-mediated process associated with thyroid dysfunction, not an infectious condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter confirming thyroid dysfunction (likely hyperthyroidism), management would involve treating the underlying thyroid disorder, typically with anti-thyroid medications or radioactive iodine. Local treatment of the skin lesions with topical corticosteroids under occlusion may be considered for symptomatic relief. It\u0027s important to note that pretibial myxoedema can persist or even first appear after treatment of hyperthyroidism, and may require long-term dermatological follow-up.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pretibial myxoedema is a dermatological manifestation of Graves\u0027 disease, characterized by thickened, waxy skin on the anterior lower legs.","The presence of pretibial myxoedema should prompt investigation for thyroid dysfunction.","Management of pretibial myxoedema primarily involves treating the underlying thyroid disorder and providing symptomatic relief."],"references":["Jennal L. Johnson; Diabetes Control in Thyroid Disease. Diabetes Spectr 1 July 2006; 19 (3): 148\u2013153.  Available at: https://diabetesjournals.org/spectrum/article/19/3/148/2031/Diabetes-Control-in-Thyroid-Disease","Croker E, McGrath S, Rowe C. Thyroid disease. Australian Journal of General Practice 2021 (50).  Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/getattachment/ba7e8d21-bf74-4e96-9b9b-1811279c27e3/Thyroid-disease-Using-diagnostic-tools-effectively.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91937"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14093"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20985"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20985","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20985"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/LBkhOAEsVMefGorvZ5oVunzd1UEPj6.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/LBkhOAEsVMefGorvZ5oVunzd1UEPj6.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":768,"height":1024}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91937","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91937"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-22T15:26:45+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-22T15:27:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6761"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109562"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://a